=========================================================
DANGLING POINTER (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
A Dangling Pointer is a pointer that points to memory that has already
been deallocated or is no longer valid.

Interview Line:
"A dangling pointer points to invalid memory."

=========================================================
HOW DOES A DANGLING POINTER OCCUR?
=========================================================

1. Deleting dynamically allocated memory.
2. Returning address of a local variable.
3. Variable going out of scope.

=========================================================
CASE 1: AFTER delete
=========================================================

int* ptr = new int(10);

delete ptr;

// ptr still contains old address
cout << *ptr;      // Undefined Behavior

Memory:

Before delete:

ptr ----> [10]

After delete:

ptr ----> X (Invalid Memory)

ptr becomes a Dangling Pointer.

=========================================================
SOLUTION
=========================================================

delete ptr;
ptr = nullptr;

=========================================================
CASE 2: RETURNING ADDRESS OF LOCAL VARIABLE
=========================================================

int* fun()
{
    int x = 10;

    return &x;      // WRONG
}

int* ptr = fun();

cout << *ptr;       // Undefined Behavior

Reason:
x is destroyed after function returns.

=========================================================
CASE 3: VARIABLE GOES OUT OF SCOPE
=========================================================

int* ptr;

{
    int x = 10;

    ptr = &x;
}

cout << *ptr;       // Undefined Behavior

Reason:
x no longer exists.

=========================================================
WHY IS DANGLING POINTER DANGEROUS?
=========================================================

May cause:
• Crashes (Segmentation Fault)
• Garbage values
• Memory corruption
• Unpredictable bugs
• Security vulnerabilities

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

int* ptr = new int(100);

delete ptr;

cout << *ptr;

Possible Outputs:
• Crash
• Garbage value
• Sometimes 100

All are:

Undefined Behavior.

=========================================================
UNDEFINED BEHAVIOR (UB)
=========================================================

Compiler gives NO guarantees.

Program may:
• Work
• Crash
• Produce random output

=========================================================
HOW TO AVOID DANGLING POINTERS?
=========================================================

1. Set pointer to nullptr after delete.

delete ptr;
ptr = nullptr;

---------------------------------------------------------

2. Never return address of local variables.

Wrong:

return &x;

---------------------------------------------------------

3. Avoid storing addresses of objects whose lifetime ends.

---------------------------------------------------------

4. Prefer Smart Pointers.

unique_ptr
shared_ptr

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

std::unique_ptr<int> ptr =
    std::make_unique<int>(10);

Automatic cleanup.

No dangling pointer.

=========================================================
DANGLING POINTER vs WILD POINTER
=========================================================

Feature               Dangling Pointer          Wild Pointer
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Meaning               Points to invalid memory  Uninitialized pointer
Initialization        Was valid earlier         Never initialized
Example               After delete              int* ptr;
Danger                High                      High

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

Wild Pointer:

int* ptr;

Dangling Pointer:

int* ptr = new int(10);

delete ptr;

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is a Dangling Pointer?

Answer:
A pointer that points to memory that is no longer valid.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. How does a Dangling Pointer occur?

Answer:
1. After delete
2. Returning local variable address
3. Object going out of scope

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Why is it dangerous?

Answer:
Because accessing invalid memory causes Undefined Behavior.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. How do you avoid Dangling Pointers?

Answer:

