=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (20 Seconds)
=========================================================

A Dangling Pointer is a pointer that refers to memory that has already
been freed or whose lifetime has ended. It commonly occurs after delete,
returning addresses of local variables, or when objects go out of scope.
Dereferencing a dangling pointer leads to Undefined Behavior and may
cause crashes or memory corruption. A common practice is to set pointers
to nullptr after deletion and use smart pointers whenever possible.

